Journal of Petroleum Science and Engineering

Volume 151, March 2017, Pages 330-340

Characterization of asphaltene deposition process in flow loop apparatus; An experimental investigation and modeling approach

Author links open overlay panel, , ,
https://doi.org/10.1016/j.petrol.2017.01.009Get rights and content

Highlights

  • •

    A experimental setup was constructed to study the asphaltene deposition process.

  • •

    The pressure drop was recorded to observe the effect of deposit layer on pressure difference.

  • •

    The effective parameters of asphaltene deposition were studied.

  • •

    A mathematical model was proposed to account for experimental observation.

Abstract

This paper describes the results of experimental tests in co-injection of precipitant agent/oil through a flow-loop setup to measure and characterize the deposition of precipitated asphaltenes along in-line test section. To do this, a novel experimental flow loop setup was designed and constructed to carry out the turbulent flow of oil (Re up to ≈7500) at desired oil-precipitant volumetric dilution ratio (DR), volumetric rate of flow and radial temperature gradient of the test section. Since the formation of deposit layer makes it difficult for the oil flow along the tube, change in pressure difference across the test section of setup was recorded along the time to measure the amount and extent of deposition process at desired condition. The experimental results revealed that, while radial temperature gradient of tube does not affect deposition process much, increasing the velocity of fluid across the tube further sweeps the precipitated particles from vicinity of wall before they have enough time to stick in contrary to oil-precipitant ratio; where the deposition rate is enhanced with increasing DR. Furthermore, these observations were thoroughly analyzed and with utilizing the concept of deposition efficiency, a new mathematical model proposed and verified for prediction of asphaltene deposition rate. The results of this work provide better insight into dynamics of asphaltene deposition and could create a better framework for conducting forthcoming experiments and developing new models of asphaltene deposition in pipelines.

1. Introduction

Asphaltene deposition in producing wells, pipes, and surface facilities have been a serious problem with a wide economic import to the oil industry. Deposition of asphaltene on the wall of production tubing (Abouie et al., 2015, Eskin et al., 2011, Kor and Kharrat, 2016) or in pores of reservoir (Civan, 2001, Darabi et al., 2014, Fallahnejad and Kharrat, 2015, Saraji et al., 2010) reduces available space to oil flow and subsequently, oil production rate decreases.

Asphaltene is the heaviest component of petroleum liquid and known as insoluble in alkanes such as n-pentane (C5) or n-heptane (C7), but soluble in aromatic solvents such as toluene, benzene or pyridine (Mullins et al., 2007). Generally, asphaltenes are stable in oil phase at reservoir condition. Variation in temperature, pressure and composition of oil can induce asphaltene instability. Asphaltene stability in crude oil has been subject of investigations over many years (Hirschberg et al., 1984, Nghiem and Coombe, 1997, Tavakkoli et al., 2013, Victorov and Firoozabadi, 1996). Asphaltene stability models can be classified as either thermodynamic or scaling models (Jafari et al., 2013). The cubic equation of states (Kohse et al., 2000, Nghiem et al., 1993, Tavakkoli et al., 2009), Micellization theory (Victorov and Firoozabadi, 1995) , PC- SAFT equation of state (Abouie et al., 2016, Assareh et al., 2016, Gross and Sadowski, 2001, Panuganti et al., 2012) and CPA equation of state (Li and Firoozabadi, 2010; Nasrabadi et al., 2013) are the example of the models have been used to study asphaltene precipitation thermodynamically. On the other hand, scaling models are based on aggregation and gelation phenomena (Ghahfarokhi, 2016, Sahimi et al., 1997). Asphaltene precipitation or deposition is often reported interchangeably; however, the difference is well defined. Precipitation is defined as solid phase formation from the bulk liquid phase, primarily as a function of thermodynamic variables (i.e., temperature, pressure, and composition). Deposition, however, is known as the creation and growth of a deposited layer on a surface. Therefore, precipitation is a prerequisite to asphaltene deposition, but it is not a sufficient condition for deposition (Kor et al., 2016). Much research work has been conducted in the area of asphaltene precipitation in the past several decades, although the mechanism of asphaltene deposition is still not well-understood (Juyal et al., 2005). According to Buckley. (2012), an experimental investigation on asphaltene deposition can be classified in two main geometries: tubes of capillary (Boek et al., 2008, Broseta et al., 2000; Nabzar and Aguiléra, 2008a, Nabzar and Aguiléra, 2008b; Wang et al., 2004) or larger dimensions (Alboudwarej et al., 2004, Jamialahmadi et al., 2009) and Taylor −Couette (TC) cells (Akbarzadeh et al., 2011b, Zougari et al., 2006). The summary of benefits and limitations of performing experiments at each geometry is explained in Table 1.

1.1. Capillary tests

Broseta et al. (2000) constructed the capillary setup of asphaltene deposition and performed experimental tests by co-injecting the various ratio of heptane and xylene into the 100 ft long stainless steel capillary at low shear rates. The pressure drop measurements were used to detect the asphaltene deposition onset and also asphaltene deposition envelope while the qualitative discussion was made about the rate of asphaltene deposition and removal. Wang et al. (2004) concluded that increasing molecular weight of asphaltene precipitant leads to the higher amount of deposition material in 0.02-in. stainless steel capillary. For example, asphaltenes precipitated by n-C15 cause much more deposition than an n-C7 agent. Nabzar and Aguiléra, 2008a, Nabzar and Aguiléra, 2008b studied the effect of a wide range of shear rates on the kinetics of asphaltene deposition in capillary flow. They showed that there are two critical shear rates that affect deposit creation: at low shear rates up to first critical shear rate the deposition is in diffusion-controlled regime, whereas beyond the firsts critical shear rate to the second critical, the deposition of colloidal asphaltene is more sensitive to shear rate than the previous regime while both critical shear rates depend on stability of asphaltene in the mixture. In the most recent work, Hashmi et al. (2015) introduced a new deposition model suggesting that asphaltene deposition on the metal surface is governed by the diffusion-driven mechanism. Asphaltene deposition was assessed by injecting a mixture of asphaltene precipitant agent and oil into a small capillary tube, which led to asphaltene deposition. Measurement of pressure drop across the pipe was used to understand dynamics of asphaltene deposition. The agreement was found between model predictions and experimental data. However, the model was developed for laminar flow, and further investigation is required to apply the model to turbulent flow of oil.

1.2. Taylor - couette cell tests

The cell, which is based on Taylor-Couette (TC) flow principles, was designed to simulate the hydrodynamic (e.g. turbulence, shear) and thermal (temperature and heat transfer) characteristics of oil in production lines (Zougari et al., 2006). Initially, the deposition test in the TC cell was performed in batch mode (closed) where the Cell containing the STO was displaced with live oil and the spindle is turned on and its rotational speed is set to desired shear rate (Akbarzadeh et al., 2011a). However, for oil with low asphaltene content, the amount of obtained asphaltene was a very small thus interpretation of tests was difficult. In order to overcome the limitation, later work was done with supplying fresh sample during the course of a test in flow through mode which produced larger amounts of asphaltene deposit. They found that shear has a significant impact on deposition in TC cell where the rate of asphaltene deposition is smaller at a pressure close to onset point than pressure close to bubble point of reservoir fluid (Akbarzadeh et al., 2011a).

1.3. Pipe-circular

Jamialahmadi et al. (2009) utilized the thermal approach to measure the rate of asphaltene deposition via the measurements of the heat transfer coefficient and the thermal resistance of deposited asphaltene in the pipe-circular flow. They proposed Arrhenius type of equation for adhesion force between flocculated asphaltene and metal surface and the proposed model was verified with results of experimental data.

This work tries to characterize the deposition of n-alkane induced asphaltene particles during both laminar and turbulent flow of oil at the different operational conditions. The rest of the paper first explains the material of the work and the detail of constructed setup to perform the tests. Then, we provided and discussed results of experimental data which led to proposing a new model to account for our observation.

2. Experimental

2.1. Experimental apparatus

2.1.1. Experimental setup

In this work, a new experimental setup was designed and assembled in the Research Center of the Petroleum University of Technology. This setup was utilized to quantify the rate of asphaltene deposition at various diluted oil sample and also the different velocity of flowing fluid. The schematic diagram of this experimental setup is shown in Fig. 1. The foremost element of this setup is Yokogawa differential pressure transmitter with is able to accurately record the pressure difference between up and downstream of the test section. In addition, because of long test duration, data logger of Bite Company was utilized to constantly record the temperature of ambient, pipe surface, flowing oil and differential pressure versus time. These data are sent to the computer in order to save data on SD card and also plot the figures. The other main elements of this setup is described briefly in the followings:

2.1.2. Pumps

Centrifugal pump was used in the setup in order to circulate the flowing fluid in the operational loop. The pump from Brook Company with AC electrical current and 2 hp electrical power was utilized to conduct the high flow rate circulation of flowing fluid. The maximum flow rate of the pump is about 5000–6000 cc/s and bypass line was used to adjust the required flow rate. Another Centrifugal pump with DC current was used to circulate the flow in low flow rate. The speed of impeller rotation can be adjusted in this pump where the maximum flow rate of 1 lit/s can be achieved.

2.1.3. Test section

A vertical pipe with a length of 100 cm and pipe diameter of 1.48 cm (OD) was used in designing the asphaltene deposition set-up. However, 75 cm of this tube was considered as a test section and pressure transmitter lines were connected to the tube with 75 cm distance from each other. The tube was manufactured from stainless steel in order to prevent the corrosion.

2.1.4. Tank

A tank with a volume of about 60 liters was directly connected to the centrifugal pump. Thistank was used to mix the crude oil and n-hexane.

2.1.5. Capillary viscometer

The viscosity was measured using glass capillary viscometers (Cannon-Fenske Opaque) suitable for dark fluids such as crude oil and oil-n-hexane mixtures. In this work, the glass viscometers manufactured and calibrated by the Industrial Research Glassware Ltd. Were used. At least three different runs with fresh samples were made for each solution to ensure reproducibility of the obtained experimental data.

2.2. Materials and fluid properties

In this study, asphaltenic crude oil sample was collected from an oil field in the southwest of Iran. In this field, asphaltene deposition problem in oil wells was reported as a common problem. The composition of the oil is presented in Table 2. The crude has a GOR of 339.28 SCF/STB and molecular weight of 169 at live condition.

The molecular weight of residual oil was measured through Freezing Point Depression method which is 285 g/mol. The last step of IP 143 was used to measure the density of asphaltene. Within that step, we placed a mixture of asphaltene and toluene at calibrated tube and was heated to 70 °C. Then, after evaporating the toluene volume and weight of residual asphaltene was used to measure the asphaltene density which was 1.07 g/cc.

2.3. Experimental procedure

2.3.1. Measurement of weight percent of precipitated asphaltene

In this work, the weight percent of precipitated asphaltene (W) must be measured in a different solvent to oil ratio known as dilution ratio (DR). In this work, weight percent of precipitated asphaltene at a range of (DR) from 0.2 to 3.0 was measured and recorded. To do this, the specific volume of cm3 of a normal alkane with a six carbon number (n-hexane) is added to 1 g of oil to meet the desired (DR), and after conducting the specific procedure, the weight percent of precipitated asphaltene (W) is determined. The procedure and the detail of measuring the (W) are shown schematically in Fig. 3. The tests were repeated at the temperatures of 20, 25 and 30 °C by adjusting the batch temperature to provide the W at different ranges of temperature and dilution ratio (DR). The temperature range of 20–30 °C was used in this study to prevent the partial vaporization of n-hexane which occurs at the temperature higher than 30 °C.

2.3.2. Procedure of conducting the experiments in the designed setup

The experimental procedure of the designed setup is summarized as follows:

The dead oil is mixed with precipitant (n-hexane) at specific dilution ratio. The mixer is turned on to start mixing the solution of n-hexane and oil. Then the controller of the cooler is adjusted at the required temperature. This mixing is continued for 5 h to reach the stability in particle size distribution of asphaltenes and also reach the thermal equilibrium. It was observed that the mixing the mixture in the tank was an effective process in this work, since both mixer and flow coming back from the test section contribute to mixing the solution. Thereafter, the DC pump is turned up and the flow rate is adjusted to the required value and data logger records the differential pressure.

3. Results and discussions

3.1. Determination of onset of asphaltene precipitation

In order to utilize the application of viscosity as means to measure the onset of asphaltene precipitation, the oil sample was diluted in various ratio with a precipitant agent (n-hexane). Results of glass capillary tests for DR ratio ranging from 0 cc/g until 0.6 g/cc are shown in Fig. 4. In our test, the change in the viscosity of mixture of (dead oil+toluene) was also measured and plot in Fig. 4 to specify the exact point that mixture of oil sample with precipitating agent start to deviate the normal curve as soon as solid asphaltene start to separate. (Beyond the onset point, viscosity does not reduce in the normal condition since solid precipitation makes the additional restriction to flow of oil mixture and offset the effect of dilution partly). The DR around 0.18 cc/g indicates the beginning of solid formation and was considered as an onset of asphaltene precipitation (Detail of the method in determining the onset of asphaltene precipitation can be found somewhere else (Escobedo and Mansoori, 1995). Therefore, all subsequent oils were diluted in DR ratio greater than 0.18 in order to assure precipitation of asphaltene particles from oil during conducting deposition experiments.

3.2. Scaling equation model

After measurement of the onset of asphaltene precipitation, prediction of weight percent of precipitated asphaltene at DR higher than onset point is also necessary. The fractal aggregation approach was used in this work to correlate the results of the titration of dead oil with normal hexane at different temperatures. Sahimi et al. (1997) and coworkers (Mozaffarian et al., 1997, Rassamdana et al., 1996) demonstrated that all titration curves of asphaltenic dead oil with solvents (n-alkane) will collapse into a single universal third order polynomial function (Jamialahmadi et al., 2009):(1)Y=A0+A1X+A2X2+A3X3Where the constant parameters A0toA3 denote the coefficients of the function. The three main parameters of titration of dead oil curves are the solvent to oil dilution ratio Rm, weight percent of precipitated asphaltene W and the molecular weight of the solvent. Rassamdana et al. (1996) reduced these three parameters into two variables X and Y of the scaling equation:(2)X=RmMz(3)Y=WRmz′

z and z′ are two adjustable parameters which must be tuned to obtain the best fit of the experimental data. Jamialahmadi and Ahmadi (2003) modified the scaling equations and for titration curves of Iranian crude oils with various alkanes, found:(4)X=RmM0.25T0.4(5)Y=W(M.Rv)−0.4

In this work, the X and Y defined in Eqs. (4), (5) were used in Eq. (1) to construct the single master curve. The result of experimental data at new axes (X, Y) in Fig. 5, suggests that all data collapse on a single curve which provides the excellent fit for the data. This obtained curve is third order polynomial with R2 equals to 0.9948 and is as follows:(6)Y=15926X3−620X2+1096.6X−3.4736

In this work, Eq. (6) was used to predict the concentration of precipitated asphaltenes in oil under various operating conditions.

3.3. Experimental data of deposition tests

The measurements of pressure drop across the pipe of radius R and length L were conducted at different flow rates, asphaltene concentrations, and temperature gradients. Table 4 provides the information about operation condition of all performed tests.

In order to record more sensible values, the measurement of pressure drop was non-dimensionalized and changed as the below:(7)Δp*=Δp−Δp0Δp0×100

∆p is a pressure drop across the tests section, ∆p0 is a pressure drop across the test section at beginning of tests and, ∆p* is called deltapstar through the whole manuscript. Commonly, tests were performed at different oil temperatures to understand the effect of flowing fluid’s temperature on asphaltene deposition process. Although, in this work, it was considered that the oil temperature mainly affects the dilution ratio (DR) and precipitation process. Therefore, the temperature difference between flowing oil and test section’s temperature were investigated to find the effect of temperature gradient on deposition process. In the tests 1, 2 and 3 temperature differences were maintained at 20 °C, 10 °C and 1 °C where setting dilution ratio and the volumetric rate at 0.25 and 55 cc/s. The results of Fig. 6 show that although a minor difference is observed in the shape∆ of pressure buildup among three tests, the final increase in pressure drop is same for all three tests. This result proposes that temperature gradient does not affect much the dynamics of the deposition process and other factors may be responsible for the deposition process.

To further analyze the deposition process, the other two different tests were conducted to see flow rate effect on the increase in pressure drop. In test #3 where the flow rate was kept at 55 cc/s, the pressure drop shows a significant increase until the time around 4000 s and then start to decline. This observation suggests the flow restriction due to asphaltene deposition makes difficulty in the flow of fluid in the pipe. In comparison to test #3, the pressure drop reduces more slowly in test #4 where the flow rate increased five times higher. This comparison has shown in Fig. 7.

In the previous comparison, the DR ratio was kept at 0.25 cc/gr and asphaltene concentrations for the tests were 1.189 gr/cc and 1.068 gr/cc, respectively. Similar experiments were also conducted to observe the effect of oil velocity on asphaltene deposition. In the tests 5, 6, 7 the oil flow rate were 500 cc/s, 55 cc/s and 250 cc/s. In all three tests in Fig. 8, the dilution ratio was kept at 0.5. Again, as we can see the oil velocity has a significant effect on asphaltene deposition in the pipe, resulting increase in pressure drop across the pipe when oil velocity decreases.

In order to assess the effect of concentration of asphaltene in the fluid on asphaltene deposition, tests 3, 6, 9 were considered. In these tests, the volumetric flow rate was 55 cc/ s where the dilution ratio (DR) were 0.25, 0.5 and 0.75 cm3/gr, respectively. As the Fig. 9 shows, the overall deltapstar for test #3 shows the rise of pressure drop from 700 pa to 768 pa. In test #6, where the asphaltene concentration was increased from 0.01189 in test #3 to 0.01732 gr/cc in test 6, the overall pressure drop increased from 300 pa to 342 pa.

In Fig. 10 we again assessed the effect of asphaltene concentrations on the deposition of asphaltene particle when the flow rate increase to 250 cc/s rather than 55 cc/s. Again, the tests results show that the increasing the dilution ratio (which means a rise in the concentration of asphaltene particle in flow) lead to higher pressure drop along the test section. However, the results of experiments suggest that although the Cb is the important factor in determining the rate of asphaltene deposition, it has a less effect than the velocity of the fluid.

Observation of experimental data of this work lead to considering the following factors in modeling of asphaltene deposition in pipe:

  • •

    The rate of injection flow, is the most important factor in building up asphaltene thickness along the tube. In fact, increasing the flow rate causes the much more of the asphaltene particles in the vicinity of pipe surface come back again to the solution.

  • •

    Thermodynamic consideration should be considered by measuring the precipitated asphaltene content in each test. Increasing the asphaltene particle concentration in the mixture, increases the pressure drop along the pipe, indicating the severity of asphaltene deposition.

  • •

    Our experiments at different temperature gradients show that the temperature does not affect the deposition process and can be ignored. However, it should be noted that we faced an operational limit in increasing the temperature of solution (partial vaporization of n-hexane) and our claim cannot be extended to the experiments with a wider range of temperature difference.

  • •

    All experimental tests show that the pressure drop increases from the beginning of tests and reach the maximum point. After this point, which can be known as critical diameter, the pressure drop becomes constant signaling the overall deposition thickness does not change beyond this point. Beyond this point, the local shear rate becomes significant and cause the balance in the rate of deposition and erosion which lead to stop in the asphaltene deposition growth.

3.4. Analysis

In assessing the experimental behavior of tests in a pipe of radius R0, a few simplifying assumptions are made. First, it was assumed that the deposit to be uniform in the axial and radial directions. The assumption of radial uniformity neglects gravity force, which may be effective in large diameter pipes. Second, the behavior of asphaltene deposition in pipe shows that the asphaltene particles continuously deposit on the inner surface of the pipe and cause the pressure drop increase until the critical diameter where shear stress become significant. In the critical diameter and beyond that, shear removal term equals to deposition term and stop the further deposition and increasing pressure drop. In this work, our focus is on the study of deposition process before critical diameter where rate and strength of asphaltene deposition are analyzed mathematically at different operational conditions.

In order to quantify this process, the concept of deposition efficiency was utilized (Nabzar and Aguiléra, 2008a, Nabzar and Aguiléra, 2008b). The deposition efficiency, DE is a dimensionless parameter which is defined as ratio of deposition flux to incident flux is written as:(8)DE=DepositionfluxofasphalteneparticlesIncidentfluxofasphaltaneparticles=JQCbwhere J is the deposition flux, gr/s, Q is the volumetric flow rate, cc/s, and Cb is the concentration of asphaltene particles in flowing fluid, gr/cc. The deposition efficiency (DE) means the fraction of precipitated asphaltenes in the flow which deposit on tube surface during a unit of time. For instance, if we have oil flow at the rate of 1 cc/s that contains the asphaltene with a concentration of 2 gr/cc, if 1 gr of asphaltene adhere to the surface at each second, the DE will be 1/2.

The deposition flux; J, which is the rate of conversion of asphaltene particles to deposit can be expressed as the change in thickness of deposited asphaltene on the surface,(9)J=ρasphdδdtAwhere ρasph is the density of asphaltenes gr/cm3, δ is the thickness of deposit cm, and A is the accessible surface to the deposition. Integrating the Eq. (9) with the initial condition δ(0)=0, we obtain:(10)δ(t)=JtρasphA

The thickness of deposited material inside the pipe can be described as a change in inner radius of pipe along the time. Therefore, we have following equation for radius of pipe at any time after beginning of flow:(11)R(t)=R0−δ(t)

After some manipulation we have,(12)R(t)R0=1−δ(t)R0

On the other hand, the Poiseuille equation can be used for calculating pressure drop in the smooth pipe during laminar flow regime. In the case of constant flow rate the Poiseuille equation can be written as:(13)ΔPL=8μQπR4→ΔP(t)ΔP0=Rm→Rm=(R0R(t))4where μ is viscosity cp, and Q is volumetric flow rate cc/s.

Inserting Eq. (13) in Eq. (12), we have:(14)Rm=1(1−δ(t)R0)4

In the case of δ≪R0 , the Eq. (14) becomes,(15)Rm−1≃4δ(t)R0

Inserting the definition of the Rm which is the ratio of pressure drop at time t on initial pressure drop in Eq. (13), we will find the relation between the Rm and the deltapstar in our experiments:(16)Rm−1=ΔP(t)ΔP0−ΔP0ΔP0=ΔP(t)−ΔP0ΔP0=ΔP*=Δp*100

ΔP* is the normalized pressure drop. Inserting Eq. (10) in Eq. (15) we find:(17)Rm−1=Δp*100≈4JρasphAR0t=4CbQρasph2πR0LR0DEt→Δp*≃400CbQρasph2πR02LDEt

For Turbulent flow, the pressure drop calculation has a different route. The classical Wiesel-Bach equation for pressure drop due to friction along smooth pipe is written as:(18)ΔP=fl2Rρq22π2R5→ΔP(t)ΔP0=Rm→Rm=(R0R)5

Likewise, inserting Eq. (18) in Eq. (14), we have:(19)Rm=1(1−δ(t)R0)5

In this case, the Eq. (19) becomes,(20)Rm−1≃5δ(t)R0Where,(21)Rm−1=ΔP(t)ΔP0−ΔP0ΔP0=ΔP(t)−ΔP0ΔP0=ΔP*=Δp*100

Thus;(22)Rm−1=Δp*100≈5JρasphAR0t=5CbQρasph2πR0LR0DEt→Δp*≃500CbQρasph2πR02LDEt

3.5. Comparison

In our experimental tests, the pressure drop versus time has been measured. In the previous section, we introduced two equations for change in the pressure drop versus time. The first equation applies to the laminar flow and the second one is for turbulent one as follows:(23){Δp*≃400CbQρasph2πR02LDEtForlaminarflowregimeΔp*≃500CbQρasph2πR02LDEtTurbuelentflowregime

These two equations are applied to predict the pressure drop increase in the experiments along the time. For each test, all parameters all available expect the deposition efficiency term (De) which depends on the mechanism of deposition at each operational condition. This term was found through the matching of Eq. (23) with the experiments. The comparisons of experimental measurements and model predictions at the best value for deposition efficiency have shown in the Fig. 11, Fig. 12. Fig. 11 shows the comparison of test results with predictions of models when the flow regime is laminar hence, the Eq. (17) was used to predict the pressure drop calculations.

In Fig. 12, the comparisons were made in the case of the turbulent regime and Eq. (22) was used.

3.6. Modeling approach

In this section, the deposition efficiencies of all tests are investigated to find the equation for the J, the rate of asphaltene deposition. Results of deposition efficiency of tests suggest that the asphaltene concentration has a less effect than fluid flow rate to the value of deposition efficiency. As it can be seen, in tests 3, 6, 9 when the oil flow rate was kept at 55 cc/s, the corresponding deposition efficiencies were 37×10−5, 40×10−5 and 41×10−5. When the flow rate increased to 250 cc/s, the deposition efficiencies were reduced by 5 times, approximately. After reviewing and analyzing the results, it was found that the deposition efficiencies of all tests are proportional with volumetric flow rate as the follows:(24)DE∝1Q1.913→DE=F1Q1.913where F is the constant factor. On the other hand, we know that the deposition efficiency of the system is defined the ratio of rate of asphaltene deposition to incident flow of asphaltene concentration, therefore:(25)J=QCbDE=QCbF1Q1.913

In the case of fluid/surface interaction in this work, we found F equals to 0.834 with coefficient of determination (R2) equals to 0.9902, thus:(26)J=0.834CbQ0.913

The final equation, considers thermodynamics, hydrodynamics and fluid and surface interaction while keeping its simplicity and convenience. To check the consistency of equation, we can recall Jamialahmadi et al. (2009) simplified form of equation which has been derived from different methodology:(27)J=FCbQe−EaRTswhere F is a factor found from curve matching. As can be seen, the Eqs. (26), (27) are similar to each other expect at exponential term which contains the temperature of inner pipe surface. This difference can be attributed to our conclusion in the results of our experiments that temperature does not play an important role in the deposition process. On the other hand, the developed model predicts that deposition rate is related to weight percent of precipitated asphaltene linearly. This conclusion was also was found by Fogler’s research group at their latest work (Vilas et al., 2016).

4. Conclusion

In this work, the deposition of asphaltene along the tube during both turbulent and laminar regimes was investigated. In order to perform experimental tests, the new experimental set-up was designed and assembled to study the attachment of asphaltene to the inner surface of pipe through continuous measurements of pressure drop across the pipe. To induce the asphaltene precipitation from dead oil, n-alkane was used as the agent to get the asphaltene out of the oil and weight percent of precipitated asphaltene was measured and a new scaling equation was proposed to predict the asphaltene concentration at any n-alkane to dead oil (DR) ratio. Observation of experimental results showed that flow rate and asphaltene concentration are two most important factors in the rate of asphaltene deposition. It showed that, increasing the flow rate cause the attachment of asphaltene particles to the surface are decreased and more of asphaltene particles come back to the solution. On the other hand, as the more volume of agent is used, it causes the asphaltene concentration in the mixture increase thus, enhancing the deposition process. By virtue of the new concept of deposition efficiency, the experimental results were analyzed and the novel equation was formulated for deposition efficiency. The formula for deposition efficiency was utilized to predict the asphaltene deposition rate at any operational condition. This equation for the rate of asphaltene deposition is simple and robust enough to be used to monitor the problem of asphaltene deposition in oil wellbores and also oil pipelines.

Appendix: A

Derivation of formula

A Maclaurin series is a Taylor series expansion of a function around 0;f(x)=f(0)+f′(0)x+f′′(0)2!x2+f′′′(0)3!x3+...+fn(0)n!xn+...

Eq. (15), isRm=1(1−δ(t)R0)4

So, with taking δR0=x, Eq. (15):Rm=(1−x)−4

The Maclaurin series for this function when x limits to 0 is,(1−x)−4=1+4x+20x2+120x3+...

Then,limx→0(1−x)−4=limx→0(1+4x+20x2+120x3+...)=1+4x

In the case δ≪R0, x limits to 0 and we have:Rm≃1+4x→Rm−1≃4x=4δR0

  • Experimental investigation on application of industrial coatings for prevention of asphaltene deposition in the well-string

    2019, Journal of Petroleum Science and Engineering
    Citation Excerpt :

    Since asphaltenes are the most polar components of crude oil and their deposition within wellbore imposes tubing plugging with excessively high remedial costs, investigation of coatings as a preventive approach for this severe problem seems mandatory. Field and laboratory studies on asphaltene deposition profile along the wellbore show that severe deposition problems occur at specific depths with corresponding pressure and temperature within asphaltene deposition envelope (ADE) (Flom et al., 2017; Ghahfarokhi et al., 2017; Jamialahmadi et al., 2009; Kargarpour and Dandekar, 2016; Kor et al., 2017; Kor and Kharrat, 2016). If the deposition of precipitated asphaltenes is inhibited by using asphaltene-repellent surfaces in the tubing at the specified depths, the flocs will re-dissolve into crude oil when the thermodynamic conditions become appropriate during vertical flow towards wellhead and the risk of tubing plugging would be disregarded.

    2019, Fuel
    Citation Excerpt :

    For more than half of a century, several researchers have focused on a variety of asphaltene related issues (characterization, modelling, and mitigation) to address the main relevant concerns in the oil industry about the kinetics and quantity of precipitation/deposition [20–33]. Many experimental procedures and modelling approaches have been reported to describe the kinetic behaviours and thermodynamic states of asphaltenes at different thermodynamic and process conditions [13,16,34–40]. In general, the common approaches to model asphaltene precipitation are classified into two main categories, including thermodynamic solubility techniques and colloidal-based models.
